#### **RECURSION**
*  For every (i, j), there are two possibilites of movement : DOWN (i+1, j) & RIGHT (i, j+1)

* **INVALID BASE CASES:**
	1. 	If index i or index j is out of bounds.

	2. 	If (i, j) cell has an obstacle.

		***In all these cases, the number of unique paths is 0.***

*  **VALID BASE CASE:**

	1. If (i, j) cell is our destination cell(m-1, n-1), 

	      ***The number of unique path is 1.***



Unique paths for Down Move = func(i+1, j) 
Unique paths for Right Move = func(i, j+1)
			***Total unique paths = Down Moves + Right Moves = func(i+1, j) + func(i, j+1)***


```
 class Solution {
    int m,n;
    int[][] grid;
    public int recurse(int i, int j) {
        if(i==m || j==n || grid[i][j]==1)
            return 0; // Invalid case
        if(m-1==i && j==n-1)
            return 1; //Valid case
        return recurse(i, j+1)+recurse(i+1, j);
    }
    public int uniquePathsWithObstacles(int[][] obstacleGrid) {
        m = obstacleGrid.length;
        n = obstacleGrid[0].length;
        grid = obstacleGrid;
        return recurse(0, 0);
    }
}
```
This will have exponential time complexity. 

#### **Optimization using Memoization (Top-Down)**
There are many cells for which the value is computed more than once.

So, after the value for a certain cell (i, j) is computed, we can store the value and return that value later on.

```
class Solution {
    Integer dp[][];
    int m,n;
    int[][] grid;
    public int recurse(int i, int j) {
        if(i == m || j == n || grid[i][j] == 1)
            return 0;
		if(dp[i][j] != null)
            return dp[i][j]; //return the already computed value for cell (i, j)
        if(m-1 == i && j == n-1)
            return dp[i][j] = 1;
        return dp[i][j] = recurse(i, j+1) + recurse(i+1, j); //store value for cell (i, j)
    }
    public int uniquePathsWithObstacles(int[][] obstacleGrid) {
        m = obstacleGrid.length;
        n = obstacleGrid[0].length;
        grid = obstacleGrid;
        dp = new Integer[m][n];
        return recurse(0, 0);
    }
}

